summary_points: 1. As of May 3, 2025, Ross Stores, Inc. had $3,848,990,000 in total cash, cash equivalents, and restricted cash and cash equivalents.

2. During the three-month period ending May 3, 2025, the company repurchased 2.0 million shares of common stock for $262.5 million (excluding excise tax), leaving $787.5 million available for future repurchases under its existing program.

3.  Pending class/representative action lawsuits alleging wage and hour law violations remain unresolved as of May 3, 2025; however, management believes their resolution will not materially impact the company's financial position.

1. On June 10, 2025, a Canadian court ordered NOVA Chemicals Corporation to pay Dow Inc. approximately USD $1.2 billion in damages related to a jointly owned ethylene asset.
2. This is in addition to a prior payment of approximately USD $1.08 billion by NOVA to Dow in 2019.
3. The judgment is subject to appeal, posing a risk to Dow receiving the full payment anticipated in the fourth quarter of 2025.

1. As of June 6, 2025, Realty Income Corporation had $4.6 billion in liquidity, comprised of $687.4 million in cash and cash equivalents, $748.1 million in unsettled ATM forward equity, and $3.2 billion in available credit facilities.
2.  The company's June 6, 2025 liquidity included £647.0 million and €936.0 million in borrowings denominated in Sterling and Euro, respectively, under its credit facilities.

3. The filing contains forward-looking statements regarding the company's growth strategies, acquisitions, dispositions, re-leases, developments, future operations, share repurchases, dividend payments, and market trends, all subject to various risks and uncertainties.
1. Warner Bros. Discovery (WBD) completed debt tender offers and consent solicitations on June 9th, 2025, aiming to allocate debt and finalize M&A plans post-spin-off.
2. Full participation in the tender offers is expected to result in approximately $800 million in CODI cash taxes for WBD.
3.  WBD must sell its remaining stake in Simon & Schuster within three to five years to maintain the tax advantages of the spin-off; failure to do so could jeopardize these benefits.
1. Dan Hines, Costco's Senior Vice President, Corporate Controller, and Principal Accounting Officer, will retire on June 30, 2025, remaining a Senior Vice President until January 2026.

2. Tiffany Barbre has been appointed as the new Senior Vice President, Corporate Controller, and Principal Accounting Officer, effective July 1, 2025, with an annual base salary of $340,000 and an estimated target value of $2 million in restricted stock units for fiscal 2026.

3.  Ms. Barbre's appointment to the role of Senior Vice President, Corporate Controller, and Principal Accounting Officer, carries with it the risk of potential disruption during the transition period.
1. Daniel Pinto, President of JPMorgan Chase, was elected to Johnson & Johnson's Board of Directors, effective July 1, 2025.
2. In fiscal year 2024, Johnson & Johnson paid JPMorgan Chase approximately $39.2 million for banking services.
3. Mr. Pinto will serve as Vice Chairman of JPMorgan Chase until his retirement at the end of 2026.

1. Corpay, Inc. appointed Peter Walker as its new Chief Financial Officer (CFO), effective July 21, 2025, with an annual base salary of $600,000 and significant equity grants totaling $7,205,360 in grant date fair value.
2.  Alissa Vickery, the interim CFO, will return to her role as Chief Accounting Officer upon Walker's appointment.

3.  Peter Walker's compensation package includes a substantial amount of performance-based restricted stock and stock options, vesting contingent upon achieving specified performance metrics in 2025, 2026, 2027, and 2028.
1. On June 10, 2025, WEC Energy Group, Inc. issued $900,000,000 of 3.375% Convertible Senior Notes due 2028, including $125,000,000 from the exercise of an option to purchase additional notes.

2.  Initially, a maximum of 8,588,520 shares of common stock may be issued upon conversion of the notes, based on an initial conversion rate of 9.5428 shares per $1,000 principal amount, subject to adjustments.
3.  The notes are senior unsecured obligations of the company, ranking senior to subordinated debt, equal to other unsecured debt, and junior to secured debt and subsidiary liabilities.

1. At T-Mobile US, Inc.'s June 6, 2025 Annual Meeting, 13 director nominees were elected to serve until the 2026 Annual Meeting, with varying levels of shareholder support ranging from 894,014,888 votes for André Almeida to 1,021,824,878 votes for Letitia A. Long.

2. Deloitte & Touche LLP's appointment as T-Mobile's independent auditor for the fiscal year ending December 31, 2025, was ratified by a vote of 1,086,139,654 for, 1,044,559 against, and 884,109 abstentions.
3.  The filing does not contain any specific future impacts or risks, nor does it mention regulatory or legal developments.
1. Target Corporation closed the sale of $1 billion in notes on June 10, 2025, consisting of $500 million in 4.350% notes due 2028 and $500 million in 5.250% notes due 2036.
2.  Net proceeds from the note sale were $498.75 million for the 2028 notes and $495.77 million for the 2036 notes (before transaction expenses and after underwriting fees).
3. The sale of the notes was registered under an existing automatic shelf registration statement filed with the SEC on November 22, 2023.
1. On June 5, 2025, Delta Air Lines completed a public offering of $2 billion in unsecured notes, with $1 billion maturing in 2028 and $1 billion in 2030.
2.  A portion of the net proceeds ($1.65 billion) from the note sale will be used to repay borrowings under the unsecured Payroll Support Program loan.
3. The indenture includes covenants limiting Delta's ability to incur liens and engage in mergers, subject to exceptions, and contains standard event of default provisions.
